ce:section.ce:para:
High Intensity Focused Ultrasound (HIFU) is a promising non-invasive ultrasound technique which has been used to thermally necrose soft tissue [1,2]. Recent in vivo studies on kidney, prostrate, heart and liver have reported that mechanical tissue fractionation with a high degree of precision can also be achieved by HIFU [3-11]. This technique is known as histotripsy and utilises a number of micro or millisecond-long ultrasound pulses with high acoustic peak positive (P+
                     ) and negative (P-
                     ) pressures at the HIFU focus to fractionate soft tissue [12,13]. For histotripsy, peak pressure values of P+
                      > 40 MPa and P−
                      of <10–15 MPa at the focus are typically employed which are comparable to those in the shockwaves used in lithotripsy for kidney stone fragmentation [14,15].

After the formation of a boiling bubble at 3.47 ms, its size gets larger and larger over each acoustic cycle (Fig. 7i–r). Fig. 9
                         shows the simulated radius vs time curve obtained from the present bubble model, demonstrating a qualitative agreement between the simulation and the experimental results. Calculated strain induced on the tissue phantom by this bubble growth is above the fractional strain of liver reported (Fig. 10
                        ). Following the rectified growth event, a cavitation cluster in front of the primary boiling bubble toward the HIFU transducer (indicated by the red arrow in Fig. 7t) and a secondary boiling bubble (indicated by the red arrow in Fig. 7u) within the HIFU focal region are visible at 5.17 ms and 5.21 ms respectively, progressing toward the HIFU transducer until the HIFU insonation ceases at 10 ms. Though the bubble activities beyond the pixel resolution of 128 × 32 (24 μm/pixel) used in the present experimental set up cannot be captured, an overall shape of a tadpole like region occupied by the cavitation clouds and the boiling bubbles for a head and a tail respectively can be observed in the gel phantom at the end of the HIFU exposure (Fig. 7w). High speed camera experimental results showing the formation of a well-defined tadpole-shaped lesion in an optically transparent tissue phantom resulting from boiling histotripsy with a larger pixel resolution of 1028 × 128 (24 μm/pixel) and a lower frame rate of 15,000 fps used are available in our previous study [24].
